      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Commercial FEA software (Ansys Mechanical) with documented V&V, version control, and audit trail. Required gradation 2 for medium model risk.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R1 used with FDA-recognized V&V documentation. Version-controlled input decks maintained in institutional repository. Software qualification records reviewed and found compliant with ASME V&V 10 and 40 requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems solved with known analytical solutions; convergence of numerical scheme confirmed for linear elastic structural problems.",
      "rationale": "Patch test and cantilever beam benchmark problems solved prior to construct analysis. Numerical results agreed with analytical solutions to within 0.3%, confirming code correctness for the element types and material models employed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrating QoI change < 5% between successive refinements; Richardson extrapolation applied.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study performed on pedicle screw shank and rod junction regions. QoI (peak von Mises stress, construct stiffness) changed by 1.8% between medium and fine meshes. Richardson extrapolation yielded discretization error estimate of 0.9% for stiffness QoI."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Residual convergence criteria tightened to 1e-6; energy convergence monitored for nonlinear steps.",
      "rationale": "Direct sparse solver employed for linear load steps. For nonlinear contact iterations, force and displacement residuals converged to 1e-6 relative tolerance. Energy norm monitored and confirmed monotonic decrease. No divergence events observed across 11 model instances."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent review of model setup by second analyst; documented modeling protocol followed.",
      "rationale": "Modeling protocol document version 2.3 followed for all 11 construct instances. Independent analyst reviewed boundary conditions, material assignments, and contact definitions against protocol checklist. Two discrepancies identified and corrected prior to final runs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum mechanics representation of metallic implant components appropriate for quasi-static loading; contact mechanics at screw-rod interface modeled with frictional contact.",
      "rationale": "Linear elastic titanium alloy (Ti-6Al-4V) material model appropriate for sub-yield loading regime. Nonlinear geometry enabled for large-displacement F1717 test configuration. Frictional contact (mu=0.2) at screw-rod interface consistent with published literature. Model form uncertainty quantified via ensemble of three independent FEA implementations."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties from certified material certificates; geometric dimensions from CMM measurements of actual test specimens; loading and boundary conditions from ASTM F1717 protocol.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus and yield strength from lot-specific material certificates (mean E=113.8 GPa). Screw and rod dimensions from CMM measurements on each of the 11 test specimens. Boundary conditions replicate F1717 fixture geometry as measured. Input uncertainty propagated via Monte Carlo sampling (n=500)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 test specimens from production lots; dimensional verification of each specimen; traceability to device design history file.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested across two independent laboratories (n=6 Lab A, n=5 Lab B). All specimens from production lots with full traceability. CMM dimensional verification confirmed specimens within drawing tolerances. Inter-laboratory variability assessed and found within acceptable range (CV < 8%)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Multiple test conditions spanning the clinical use envelope; minimum two load levels or fixture configurations.",
      "rationale": "Testing performed at a single load configuration per ASTM F1717 standard (compression-bending at 10 degrees). While the protocol is standardized, only one test condition was evaluated, resulting in achieved level below required. This gap is acknowledged and addressed through conservative acceptance bounds and model uncertainty quantification. Residual risk accepted by the credibility assessment team given the standardized nature of the F1717 protocol."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Demonstration that model input parameters match experimental conditions within quantified tolerances; no systematic offset between model inputs and test specimen properties.",
      "rationale": "CMM-measured specimen dimensions used directly as model inputs. Material property inputs verified against lot certificates for each specimen. Fixture geometry digitized from laboratory photographs and compared to nominal F1717 fixture dimensions. No systematic offset identified; maximum input parameter discrepancy 1.4% for rod diameter."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval < 1.96 for all primary QoIs; percent difference < 10% for each QoI; uncertainty in validation metric explicitly characterized.",
      "rationale": "Three primary QoIs compared: construct stiffness (E/uval=0.87), yield force (max percent difference 7.1%), and force at 40 mm (E/uval=1.41). All metrics satisfy pre-established acceptance criteria. Experimental uncertainty estimated from inter-specimen and inter-laboratory variability. Model uncertainty from ensemble of three FEA implementations."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs directly linked to clinical failure modes; QoIs are the same quantities predicted in the COU.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the same QoIs used in the regulatory submission to characterize mechanical performance. These QoIs are directly linked to the clinical failure mode of construct loosening and fatigue fracture. The validation QoIs are identical to the COU prediction QoIs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation scenario geometry, material, loading, and boundary conditions representative of COU; validation model is the same model used in the COU.",
      "rationale": "Validation activity uses the identical FEA model, material models, and boundary condition implementation as the COU prediction. Test specimens are production-representative non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screws of the same design family. ASTM F1717 test configuration is the regulatory standard for this device class, directly representing the COU mechanical environment."
    }
